[{"id":"VR795712","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a circuit diagram with a battery and three identical resistors. At the top of the circuit there are 3 parallel, horizontal wire segments, each of which contains a resistor. The current in the top wire segment is I sub 1, the current in the middle wire segment is I sub 2, and the current in the bottom wire segment is I sub 3. The left ends of all three wire segments are connected to each other, and the right ends of all three wire segments are connected to each other. A battery is connected in parallel with the arrangement of resistors.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR795712.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure shows a circuit composed of a battery and three identical resistors. Which of the following correctly relates the currents <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 2\"><math alttext=\"I sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 3\"><math alttext=\"I sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span> in the resistors to the current <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub battery\"><math alttext=\"I sub battery\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>battery</mi></msub></math></span></span> in the battery, and provides reasoning that supports the stated relation?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR795712_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1, end sub, plus I sub 2, end sub, plus I sub 3, end sub, equals I sub battery\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1, end sub, plus I sub 2, end sub, plus I sub 3, end sub, equals I sub battery\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mtext>battery</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. The total amount of charge entering and exiting a junction per unit time must be equal.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1, end sub, plus I sub 2, end sub, plus I sub 3, end sub, equals I sub battery\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1, end sub, plus I sub 2, end sub, plus I sub 3, end sub, equals I sub battery\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mtext>battery</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. The potential differences across the three resistor branches sum to the potential difference of the battery, and potential difference is proportional to current.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1, end sub, equals I sub 2, end sub, which equals I sub 3, end sub, which equals I sub battery\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1, end sub, equals I sub 2, end sub, which equals I sub 3, end sub, which equals I sub battery\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mtext>battery</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. Parallel circuit branches must all have the same current.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub 1, end sub, equals I sub 2, end sub, which equals I sub 3, end sub, which equals I sub battery\"><math alttext=\"I sub 1, end sub, equals I sub 2, end sub, which equals I sub 3, end sub, which equals I sub battery\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mtext>battery</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. Current is directly proportional to potential difference, and the potential difference is the same across each parallel branch of the circuit.</p>"],"answer":0}]